1) A symposium named "ABM 2017: A symposium that advances the science of ABM" was held during April 20-22, 2017 at San Diego, California with great success: 43 Science committee members and 53 regular participants  participated in the symposium Organize a conference;

2) A state-of-the-art paper addressing ABMs was near submission, This paper addresses several compelling ABM problems and challenges at the right time.  While the use of ABMs is exploding there remains a number of unresolved challenges. With input from around 40 exceptional scientists (including modelers, users, domain experts) and 60 ABM junior scholars, this paper tackles ABM challenges and advances the science of ABM.

3) Several topical papers were near completion or in review. These papers are dealing with specific challenges confronting ABMs and pointing the way forward;

4) A website (ABM Repository that comprehensively incorporates all the resources provided by workshop participants) was developed and in maintenance;

5) One research proposal was developed and secured funding from NSF CNH program in September 2018: "CNH-L: People, Place, and Payments in Complex Human-Environment Systems (2018-2022, PI: Dr. Li An). Total budget: $1,450,000"

6) ABM 17 leaders Drs. Li An, Volker Grimm, and Billie L. Turner II proposed to launch a special issue entitled "Meeting Grand Challenges in Agent-based Complex Systems" at The Journal of Artificial Societies and Social Simulation (JASSS). Recently JASSS Editor-in-Chief Dr. Flaminio Squazzoni and the editorial board approved the special issue proposal. The special is underway and all papers are due Feb 1, 2018.

